General analysis of tank data in World of Tanks¶

What's this and how was it obtained?¶

This is an analysis of some data about tanks in World of Tanks. The data was obtained using the Wargaming.net Public API on March 2021, for patch 1.2, and was extracted by calling the method vehicles to obtain all vehicles with their list of modules, and then vehicle profile to obtain data about each configuration. A subset of the information obtained was saved as a CSV file that you can find here.

I wanted to have the information in CSV format to be able to play with it in a spreadsheet, but I quickly found that it was too much information: there are many tanks and many configurations. That's why in the end I decided to analyze it using Python (with Matplotlib, Pandas and Seaborn). Pull requests and tips for improving the code are appreciated: I know there has to be a better way... Probably, there are even errors! You can find the code in this Github repository.

What's the goal of all of this? Nothing in particular: just trying to visualize the data about the tanks and answer some questions that pique my curiosity.

Tanks per tier, class and nation¶

First question: how many tanks are there? Let's start by reading the CSV file, which has one line per tank configuration.

In [2]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from IPython.display import HTML
from matplotlib import cm

sns.set(rc={
    'figure.figsize':(18,7),
    'axes.titlesize': 18
})

df = pd.read_csv("wot_data.csv", sep=";")

# Clean up so that tanks are ordered by nation, tier and class
classes = ["Heavy", "Medium", "Light", "Destroyer", "Arty"]
df = df.replace(
    ["heavyTank", "mediumTank", "lightTank", "AT-SPG", "SPG"],
    classes
)
df["class"] = pd.Categorical(df["type"], classes, ordered=True)
df.drop("type", inplace=True, axis=1)

nations = ["Germany", "USSR", "USA", "France", "UK", "China", "Japan", "Czech", "Poland", "Sweden", "Italy" ]
df = df.replace(
    ["germany", "ussr", "usa", "france", "uk", "china", "japan", "czech", "poland", "sweden", "italy"],
    nations
)
df.nation = pd.Categorical(df["nation"], nations, ordered=True)

df.sort_values(["nation", "tier", "class"], ascending=True)

num_confs = len(df)
num_tanks = len(df.name.unique())
avg_confs_per_tank = num_confs/num_tanks

configurations than others? Let's plot a histogram.

Out[3]:
Wow! There are 685 tanks in 14522 configurations, so the average number of configurations per tank is 21.2. That's a lot of variety, but you have to take into account that when you have three radios, for instance, you are multiplying your configurations by 3 without changing the play style of the tank.

However, an interesting question is: are the configurations distributed uniformly or are there tanks with many more configurations than others? Let's plot a histogram.
In [4]:
conf_count = df.groupby("name")["name"].count()
bins = np.arange(conf_count.min(), conf_count.max()+2, 1)-0.5

ax = conf_count.hist(bins=bins)
ax.set_xlim(0, 100)
ax.set_xlabel("Number of configurations")
ax.set_ylabel("Number of tanks")
plt.title("Number of tanks per number of configurations")
_= plt.xticks(range(2, 100, 2))

So almost 300 tanks only have one configuration: they are probably premium and tier 10 tanks. We will check that later.

The next most probable value is 24 configurations, and there are even around 25 tanks with 36 configurations. But the previous histogram was cut in order to be able to distinguish the bins. Which are the tanks with more configurations? Let's see:

In [5]:
_ = conf_count.sort_values(ascending=False).head(20).plot(kind="bar", title="20 most configurable tanks")

The KV-3 is really configurable... 213 possibilities! Why is that? How many modules does it have?

In [6]:
_ = (df[df.name=="KV-3"][["gun", "engine", "radio", "turret", "suspension"]]
        .agg(['nunique']).T.sort_values(by="nunique", ascending=False)
        .plot(kind="bar", title="Number of modules for KV-3", figsize=(5,4)))

Six guns and four radios. Not bad, not bad...

Notice that combining all the modules we would get 288 configurations, but "only" 213 are valid.

Previously I guessed that there were so many tanks with only one configuration because they were tier 10 or premiums. Let's check the distribution of number of configurations per tier:

In [7]:
conf_tier_count = df.groupby(["name", "tier"]).count().reset_index()[["name", "tier", "is_premium", "short_name"]].rename(columns={"short_name": "count"})
with sns.axes_style("whitegrid"):
    ax = sns.histplot(data=conf_tier_count, x="count", hue="tier", multiple="stack", binwidth=1, edgecolor=".9", linewidth=.5,)
    _ = ax.set_xlim(0, 40)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mpl.ticker.ScalarFormatter())
    plt.title("Number of configurations per tier (all tanks)")
    _ = ax.set_xticks(range(40))

In the first column on the left, we can see that there are around 70 tier 10 tanks with only one configuration, but there are even more tier 8 tanks with one configuration. In addition, we can see around 20 tanks with only two configurations and they are either tier 1 or tier 10.

Another way to visualize this is plotting the number of occurrences of each number of configurations with a different color for each tier:

In [8]:

Let's plot the histogram only for non-premium tanks:

In [9]:
conf_tier_count = df[df.is_premium != True].groupby(["name", "tier"]).count().reset_index()[["name", "tier", "short_name"]].rename(
    columns={"short_name": "count"})
with sns.axes_style("whitegrid"):
    ax = sns.histplot(data=conf_tier_count, x="count", hue="tier", multiple="stack", binwidth=1, edgecolor=".9", linewidth=.5,)
    _ = ax.set_xlim(0, 40)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mpl.ticker.ScalarFormatter())
    plt.title("Number of configurations per tier (only non-premium tanks)")
    _ = ax.set_xticks(range(40))

We can see that all non-premium tanks with only one configuration are tier 10. But there are almost 300 tanks with only one configuration and now that we are plotting only non-premiums we only have a little more than 50... So, how many premium tanks are there?

In [10]:
gr = df[["name", "class", "dpm", "tier", "nation", "is_gift", "speed_forward", "speed_backward", "is_premium"]].groupby(["name"]).agg(
    { 'class': 'first',
      'dpm': 'max',
      'tier': 'first',
      'nation': 'first',
      'is_gift': 'first',
      'speed_forward': 'max',
      'speed_backward': 'max',
      'is_premium': 'first',
      }).reset_index()
gr["class"] = pd.Categorical(gr["class"], classes, ordered=True)
gr.nation = pd.Categorical(gr["nation"], nations, ordered=True)

premium = gr.groupby(["tier", "is_premium"]).count()["class"].reset_index().rename(columns={'class':'Tank count'})
premium.is_premium.replace(True, "Premium", inplace=True)
premium.is_premium.replace(False, "Non-premium", inplace=True)
premium_count = premium.groupby("is_premium").sum()["Tank count"]
_ = premium_count.plot(kind="pie", title="% premium tanks", autopct='%1.1f%%', colors = ['silver', 'gold'],
                       legend=False).set_ylabel("")
HTML(f'The answer is: {premium_count["Non-premium"]} premium tanks and {premium_count["Premium"]} non-premium tanks.')
Out[10]:
The answer is: 438 premium tanks and 247 non-premium tanks.

Let's plot them by tier:

In [11]:
premium_by_tier = premium.groupby(["tier", "is_premium"]).sum().unstack().fillna(0).droplevel(0, axis=1)

ax = premium_by_tier.plot.barh(stacked=True, color=['silver', 'gold'], title="Number of tanks per tier")
for rect in ax.patches:
    height = rect.get_height()
    width = rect.get_width()
    x = rect.get_x()
    y = rect.get_y()
    
    label_text = f'{int(width)}'
    
    label_x = x + width / 2
    label_y = y + height / 2
    
    # only plot labels greater than given width
    if width > 0:
        ax.text(label_x, label_y, label_text, ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12)
        
    if x > 0: # Put the total percentage only over premium tanks
        label_perc_x = x + width + 4
        total_perc = (x + width) * 100 / num_tanks
        ax.text(label_perc_x, label_y, f"{total_perc:.1f}%", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12)

_ = ax.legend(['Non-premium', 'Premium'])

Things we can see:

  • There are between 36 and 59 non-premium tanks per tier between tiers 2 and 10.

  • There is much more variation in the number of premium tanks per tier: the minimum (discarding tier 1) is at layer 4, with only 6 premium tanks, while the maximum is at layer 8, with 115 tanks, almost 25% of all tanks.

  • Almost half of premium tanks are in tier 8. This can be seen better in this pie chart:

What about the distribution of tanks per nation and class?

In [13]:
gr_nat_type = gr.groupby(["nation", "class", "is_premium"]).count().rename(columns={'dpm': 'Tank count'})["Tank count"].reset_index()
gr_nat_type.is_premium.replace(True, "Premium", inplace=True)
gr_nat_type.is_premium.replace(False, "Non-premium", inplace=True)

# Put in the "Premium" column the total of premium and non-premium: it's a hack to simulate stacked bars in sns
gr_nat_type = gr_nat_type.pivot(index=["is_premium"], columns=["nation", "class"], values="Tank count").T
gr_nat_type["Total"] = gr_nat_type["Premium"] + gr_nat_type["Non-premium"]
gr_nat_type.drop("Premium", axis=1, inplace=True)
gr_nat_type = gr_nat_type.rename(columns={'Total': 'Premium'})
gr_nat_type = gr_nat_type.stack().to_frame().reset_index().rename(columns={0: 'Tank count'})
gr_nat_type.sort_values("is_premium", ascending=False, inplace=True) # So that premium is behind non-premium

g = sns.FacetGrid(gr_nat_type, col='nation', hue='is_premium', col_wrap=4, col_order=nations, palette=['gold', 'silver'],
                 aspect=1.1)
g = (g.map(sns.barplot, "class", "Tank count", order=classes, saturation=1).add_legend())

for ax in g.axes.flatten():
    ax.tick_params(labelbottom=True, axis="x", direction="in")
    ax.set_xlabel('')
g.legend.set_title(None)
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
g.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
_ = g.fig.suptitle("Number of tanks per nation and class", size=20)

There are some apparent patterns:

  • Germany and UK: focused on mediums and tank destroyers.
  • USSR: focused on heavy tanks, although it is the nation with more tanks and the number of mediums (second class for USSR) is similar to number of mediums in Germany (first class for Germany).
  • USA: quite balanced, with a little more mediums.
  • France: focused on light tanks. Wheeled vehicles is probably the cause.
  • Chine: quite balanced, with less heavy tanks.
  • Tank destroyers and arties are usually not present in the nations most-recently added, except for Sweden, that has a tank destroyer line.

And what about the number of tanks per class independently of nation?

There are more than 200 mediums and around 150 heavies and lights. Tank destroyers lag behind at about 125, while there are only around 50 arties. The figure also shows that heavies and mediums are more balanced between premium and not-premium than the rest of the classes.

Let's see how many tanks each nation has...

Although I was under the impression that the first five nations had a similar number of tanks, USSR has almost twice the number of tanks of France.

It's also apparent that there are nations (USSR, Germany, USA) where the number of premiums is much closer to non-premiums than in others.
